	abstract = {Using {SFT} techniques, Eliashberg, Kim and Polterovich (2006) proved that if \$πR\_2{\textasciicircum}2 {\textbackslash}leq K {\textbackslash}leq πR\_1{\textasciicircum}2\$ for some integer \$K\$ then there is no contact squeezing in \${\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}{\textasciicircum}\{2n\} {\textbackslash}times S{\textasciicircum}1\$ of the prequantization of the ball of radius \$R\_1\$ into the prequantization of the ball of radius \$R\_2\$. This result was extended to the case of balls of radius \$R\_1\$ and \$R\_2\$ with \$1 {\textbackslash}leq πR\_2{\textasciicircum}2 {\textbackslash}leq πR\_1{\textasciicircum}2\$ by Chiu (2017) and the first author (2016), using respectively microlocal sheaves and {SFT}. In the present article we recover this general contact non-squeezing theorem using generating functions, a classical method based on finite dimensional Morse theory. More precisely, we develop an equivariant version, with respect to a certain action of a finite cyclic group, of the generating function homology for domains of \${\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}{\textasciicircum}\{2n\} {\textbackslash}times S{\textasciicircum}1\$ defined by the second author (2011). A key role in the construction is played by translated chains of contactomorphisms, a generalization of translated points.},
